    <item>
      <title>What a Functor Preserves and Why It Matters</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/categories/texts/what-a-functor-preserves-and-why-it-matters/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/categories/texts/what-a-functor-preserves-and-why-it-matters/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A function maps elements from one set to another. A &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/functor/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;functor&lt;/a&gt; maps elements AND their relationships from one structured world to another, preserving the structure.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;functions-forget-structure&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#functions-forget-structure&#34; class=&#34;heading-anchor&#34; aria-label=&#34;Link to this section&#34;&gt;¶&lt;/a&gt;Functions forget structure&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Consider a set of files and a set of author names. The function &amp;ldquo;first author of&amp;rdquo; maps each file to a name. It carries elements from one set to another. But it says nothing about how files relate to each other, or how author names relate to each other. The function operates on bare elements.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Is an Adjunction?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/categories/texts/what-is-an-adjunction/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/categories/texts/what-is-an-adjunction/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;An adjunction is a relationship between two operations where each partially undoes the other, but neither is a true inverse.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Start with a familiar example. Rounding down and including: the floor function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;⌊&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;⌋&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lfloor x \rfloor&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; takes a real number and gives the largest integer below it. The inclusion function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;i(n)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; takes an integer and treats it as a real number. These are connected:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34; display=&#34;block&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;⌊&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;⌋&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≥&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mspace width=&#34;1em&#34;/&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;if and only if&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mspace width=&#34;1em&#34;/&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≥&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lfloor x \rfloor \geq n \quad\text{if and only if}\quad x \geq i(n)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The floor of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is at least &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;rdquo; is the same as &amp;ldquo;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is at least &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&amp;rdquo; The floor function and inclusion are adjoint: floor is the left adjoint, inclusion is the right adjoint. Floor &amp;ldquo;freely&amp;rdquo; produces an integer from a real; inclusion &amp;ldquo;forgetfully&amp;rdquo; treats an integer as a real.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
